library(lattice)

## Loading required package: RColorBrewer

Concrete <- read.csv("Concrete_Data.csv", comment.char = "#", row.names = NULL)

Посмотрим на корреляцию признаков

levelplot(cor(Concrete)^2, par.settings = list(regions = list(col = colorRampPalette(grey(1:0)))),
          scales = list(x = list(rot = 90)), xlab = "", ylab = "")

Здесь мы видим, что основными признаками являются Cement, Water, Superplasticizer и Age. При этом, Water и Superplasticizer сильно зависимы.

xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$Age, data = Concrete)

Тут нужен factor.

Concrete$Age <- factor(log(Concrete$Age))
contrasts(Concrete$Age) <- 'contr.sum' 
xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$Superplasticizer, data = Concrete)

xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$Water, data = Concrete)

xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$BlastFurnaceSlag, data = Concrete)

xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$FlyAsh, data = Concrete)

xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$CoarseAggregate, data = Concrete)

xyplot(Concrete$ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ Concrete$FineAggregate, data = Concrete)

А здесь установим порог.

Concrete$SuperplasticizerPositive <- Concrete$Superplasticizer > 0
Concrete$WaterGreater180 <- Concrete$Water > 180

Попробуем построить линейную модель

l1 <- lm(ConcreteCompressiveStrength ~ ., data = Concrete)
l1.aic <- stepAIC(l1)

Проверим линейную модель на overfitting

train.idx <- sample(nrow(Concrete), size = nrow(Concrete) * 0.66)
Concrete.train <- Concrete[train.idx, ]
Concrete.test <- Concrete[-train.idx, ]
l1.aic.train <- lm(l1.aic$call$formula, data = Concrete.train)
rmse <- function(a, b) sqrt(mean((a - b)^2 , na.rm = TRUE))
rmse(predict(l1.aic.train, Concrete.train), Concrete.train$ConcreteCompressiveStrength)
## [1] 6.349959
rmse(predict(l1.aic.train, Concrete.test), Concrete.test$ConcreteCompressiveStrength)
## [1] 6.904302

Всё ок. А теперь выкинем CoarseAggregate
